    "policy_language_requires_deescalation": "No. \"Officers need not retreat or desist in the reasonable use of force. There is no requirement that officers use a lesser intrusive force option before progressing to a more intrusive one, as long as the force option used is objectively reasonable under the circumstances at that time. When confronted by force or resistance, an officer may use an objectively reasonable higher level of force to overcome that resistance.",
    "bans_chokeholds_and_strangleholds": 1,
    "policy_language_bans_chokeholds_and_strangleholds": "Yes. Policy limits chokeholds and carotid restraints to situations where deadly force would be authorized.\n  The \"Carotid Restraint\" may be used when other control techniques have failed or are inappropriate and deadly force may become objectively reasonable if the \"Carotid Restraint\" is not used.\"\n  \"The chokehold is prohibited as an authorized control technique to overcome resistance and shall not be used for this purpose. However, a chokehold may only be used by an officer as a deadly force option\" (See: http://www.sjpd.org/images/Chokehold_Policy_2016-002.pdf)",
    "duty_to_intervene": 0,
