    "policy_language_requires_deescalation": "No.\n  No requirement to de-escalate situations, when possible.",
    "bans_chokeholds_and_strangleholds": 0,
    "policy_language_bans_chokeholds_and_strangleholds": "No. Carotid Control Holds authorized as an intermediate force option below deadly force. \"As a defensive or control measure, the carotid restraint may be utilized by a police officer when his/her safety or the safety of another person is threatened. This restraint should be used cautiously and should be used when attempts of lesser force have been exhausted, are ineffective, or would have been inappropriate to attempt.",
    "duty_to_intervene": 1,
    "policy_language_duty_to_intervene": "Yes. \"Employees witnessing any unreasonable use of force that is unreasonable under the circumstances shall intercede to prevent the further use of force and shall inform their immediate supervisor as soon as possible.",
    "requires_warning_before_shooting": 1,
    "policy_language_requires_warning_before_shooting": "Yes. \"When practical, a verbal warning or command should be given to the suspect before the use of any force. However, the practicality or feasibility of a warning may be contingent on any exigency, threat level, or other safety considerations.\"\n \"• An officer may use deadly force to effect the arrest or prevent the escape of a suspected felon where the officer has probable cause to believe that the suspect poses a significant threat of death or serious bodily injury to the officer or others. Under such circumstances, a verbal warning should precede the use of deadly force, when feasible.",
    "restricts_shooting_at_moving_vehicles": 0,
    "policy_language_restricts_shooting_at_moving_vehicles": "No. Allows officers to shoot at moving vehicles when deadly force is not being used against others by means other than the vehicle if it's a last resort. \"There are situations in which suspects do use vehicles as weapons against officers. The safest tactical decision for officers may be to avoid the on-coming vehicle by seeking cover or moving to a position of safety. Shooting at a vehicle should ordinarily be an act of last resort and generally should only be done when other reasonable alternatives are impractical or fail. The mere movement of a vehicle toward an officer doesn’t necessarily constitute a deadly force situation.",
    "requires_comprehensive_reporting": 0,
    "policy_language_requires_comprehensive_reporting": "No. Pointing a weapon at a civilian is not required to be reported. \n  \"IV. Reporting Procedures\n  It is the intent of this policy to outline the circumstances by which force is reported. All situations that the application of force to effect an arrest or restore order, shall be properly documented (officer's\n  report, supervisorÄƒÃs use of force investigation report, administrative report, etc.). For example, if an\n  officer applies a control hold to gain or maintain control of subject, and there is neither injury nor\n  complaint of pain, the officer shall document the use of force in his/her report.",
    "requires_exhaust_all_other_means_before_shooting": 0,
    "policy_language_requires_exhaust_all_other_means_before_shooting": "No. Does not require officers to exahust other reasonable means before resorting to deadly force. \"Use of deadly force is justified in the following circumstances:\n -Officers may use deadly force to protect themselves or others from what they reasonably believe would be an immediate threat of death or serious bodily injury.\n -An officer may use deadly force to effect the arrest or prevent the escape of a suspected felon where the officer has probable cause to believe that the suspect poses a significant threat of death or serious bodily injury to the officer or others. Under such circumstances, a verbal warning should precede the use of deadly force, when feasible.",
    "has_use_of_force_continuum": 0,
    "policy_language_has_use_of_force_continuum": "1.3.1 “Any peace officer that has reasonable cause to believe that the person to be arrested has\ncommitted a public offense may use reasonable force to affect the arrest, to prevent escape, or to\novercome resistance. A peace officer who makes or attempts to make an arrest need not retreat\nor desist from his/her efforts by reason of resistance or threatened resistance of the person being\narrested; nor shall such officer be deemed the aggressor or lose his/her right to self-defense by\nthe use of reasonable force to effect the arrest or to prevent escape or to overcome resistance.”\n1.3.3 Less Lethal Force Applications\nAny application of force, which is not reasonably anticipated to result in death, shall be\nconsidered less lethal force. Less lethal force applications may include, but are not limited to,\nphysical contact (hands, body, etc.), the use of a baton, chemical agent, extended range impact\nweapon, Electronic Control Device (ECD), carotid restraint, leg restraints, improvised or\nunconventional weapons and other Less Lethal Weapons as described in General Order 1.4 .\nLess lethal force has the potential to cause injury.\n1.3.4 Deadly Force Applications\nUse of deadly force is justified in the following circumstances:\n Officers may use deadly force to protect themselves or others from what they reasonably\nbelieve would be an immediate threat of death or serious bodily injury.\n An officer may use deadly force to effect the arrest or prevent the escape of a suspected felon\nwhere the officer has probable cause to believe that the suspect poses a significant threat of\ndeath or serious bodily injury to the officer or others. Under such circumstances, a verbal\nwarning should precede the use of deadly force, when feasible.",
